complete_model_interaction.output:
First, I reasoned that responders’ decisions in the ultimatum game hinge on how much of the pie they receive relative to what they themselves contributed (and what was fairly due them).  I therefore compute, for each offer:  
- share_prop = split_self / combined_earning  
- cont_prop  = token_self / (token_self + token_opp)  

The core psychological assumption is that the decision utility increases when share_prop exceeds cont_prop, and decreases when it falls short.  We capture this with a simple linear utility function:

U = bias + kappa * (share_prop − cont_prop)

where  
• bias is an intercept capturing any baseline tendency to accept or reject offers irrespective of fairness,  
• kappa is a sensitivity parameter to deviations from contribution-based fairness.  

A logistic transform of U (temperature=1) gives the acceptance probability: P(accept)=1/(1+exp(−U)).  

<MODEL>
U = bias + kappa * (share_prop - cont_prop)
</MODEL>

